      "shell": "Brass — bright fundamental with strong projection",
      "description": "The snare drum on *Leviathan* is one of the album's most recognisable sonic signatures: a tight, cracking voice that punches through Matt Bayles' dense guitar wall without overwhelming the melodic content of Dailor's tom work. Matched to the Tama Starclassic Bubinga kit, the snare for the *Leviathan* sessions was a 14\" x 5.5\" brass-shell instrument — Tama's brass options of the era delivered the brightness and projection that the album's mix demanded.\n\nBrass shells respond quickly and with a bright top-end character that contrasts cleanly against the dark bubinga shell fundamentals. On tracks like \"Blood and Thunder,\" where the snare anchors the song's central groove against the riff's gallop, this brightness is essential — the snare must register on every backbeat with absolute clarity even when the guitars are at full density. The 5.5\" depth (shallower than the 6.5\" snare Dailor would adopt for *Crack the Skye*) prioritises attack over body, suiting the album's more direct, less atmospheric mix.\n\nGhost notes — the hallmark of Dailor's jazz-trained playing — register clearly on the *Leviathan* snare. Passages like the \"I Am Ahab\" verse groove and the breakdown sections of \"Naked Burn\" use ghost note density to create rhythmic texture beneath the main backbeats, and the brass shell's quick response makes these quiet notes audible rather than washed-out. For a jazz drummer translating jazz vocabulary into metal, the ability of the snare to speak at low velocity is not a minor detail; it is the foundation of the entire stylistic translation.\n\nMatt Bayles captured the snare with a single close microphone (likely a Shure SM57) supplemented by minimal room contribution — the dry, direct snare crack that became the album's sonic fingerprint. This production approach kept the snare anchored at the front of the mix where Dailor's intricate playing could be followed by the listener, even at the album's most chaotic moments.",
